<BaseLayout title="about / gybe.org" description="About Godspeed You! Black Emperor and this fan archive.">
  <h1 class="page-title">about</h1>
  <p class="deck">
    Godspeed You! Black Emperor is a Montreal collective whose music moves through long-form instrumental rock, field recordings, tape loops, political dread, and fragile moments of release.
  </p>

  <section class="content">
    <h2>about GY!BE</h2>
    <p>
      The group was founded in 1994 in Montreal, Canada, by guitarists Efrim Menuck and Mike Moya and bassist Mauro Pezzente. Initially formed to support a local band called Steak 72, the trio soon began developing their own musical projects.
    </p>
    <p>
      Their name comes from the 1976 documentary <em>Gottsu Supido Yu! Burakku Enpera</em> by Japanese director Mitsuo Yanagimachi. The film focuses on the lives, daily struggles, and social world of the Bosozoku motorcycle gangs in Japan.
    </p>

    <h2>about the movie</h2>
    <p>
      Popular in Japan during the 1970s, these groups were typically made up of rebellious youth. They were known for riding elaborately decorated motorcycles and for their defiant behavior. The documentary explores the hierarchical structure of these gangs, their leader figures, and the bonds among members in detail.
    </p>
    <p>
      Yanagimachi's film delves into the personal stories of the gang members, addressing themes of societal alienation, clashes with authority, and the search for self-expression among young people. Shot in black and white, the documentary captures the aesthetic of Bosozoku culture and the urbanization process in Japan at the time.
    </p>

    <h2>the first album</h2>
    <p>
      In 1994, the group released its first work, <em>All Lights Fucked on the Hairy Amp Drooling</em>. Emerging from Montreal's experimental music sphere, the album gave early hints of the artistic and political vision the band would later adopt. It was closer to an Efrim Menuck solo project than to the large collective sound that would follow.
    </p>
    <p>
      The album featured Efrim Menuck on vocals, guitar, and various instruments, Mauro Pezzente on bass guitar, and Dano Leblanc contributing acoustic guitar and an experimental technique described as "backwards hash." D.C. provided vocals for "$13.13." Mike Moya, though later a key member, did not participate in this recording.
    </p>
    <p>
      The album was released in just 33 cassette copies, distributed by hand by the band members. Its limited production turned it into a legendary object among fans. In 2022, after the full album surfaced online, the band officially released it digitally through Bandcamp and confirmed its authenticity.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
